				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I've just arrived at the answer: yes. I've optimized NewRisingSun's code about 25x and gotten my NES emulator to run full-speed on my 400MHz PowerMac using a reduced screen size (source size: 219x225 PPU pixels).
<br />
<br /><img src="http://www.io.com/~greens/temp/ntsc_nes.png" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br />I had to sacrifice the quality a bit, but it should run full-speed, size, and quality on a modern GHz PC. Only about 4% of CPU time is spent doing actual emulation; the rest is spent on this NES-&gt;NTSC-&gt;RGB algorithm. I'll release the code once I'm done with this last round of optimization. I've also got one more idea for an approximation that might be many times faster.
<br />
<br />The algorithm is <em>very</em> intensive. It converts source NES pixels to the raw NTSC signal, then converts that to RGB. The most difficult speed drain to eliminate is the filtering to extract the luminance and chrominance information. I was able to find an <a href="http://www.ph.tn.tudelft.nl/~lucas/publications/1995/SP95TYLV/SP95TYLV.pdf" class="postlink">IIR-based gaussian filter</a> (<a href="http://home.arcor.de/peter.heckert/unsharp2-0.11.c" class="postlink">C implementation</a>) that achieves symmetricality by being run in both directions, which gave the last major speedup.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

